Honestly, most of us are so used to casual texting that we sometimes forget emails aren’t the same. A small mistake in how we write something online can actually create unnecessary problems. For example, imagine a student sending a message to a professor saying, “Send deadline ahead pls” or “I can’t submit, give extension,” without any proper subject, greeting, or explanation. From the student’s side, it might feel quick and normal, but to the professor, it can come across as careless or even a bit rude.
Because of this, the professor might ignore the email or not fully understand the situation, which can end up affecting the student’s grades.
The truth is, fixing this doesn’t require anything complicated. Just writing a proper subject, starting with a respectful greeting, explaining the reason clearly, and ending politely can change everything. It shows that you’re serious and respectful.
This made me realize that good digital communication is not about using difficult words—it’s just about being clear, polite, and a little more thoughtful in how we express ourselves online.

